  "prompt": "How much cubic meter of cement, sand required for 12mm cement sand plaster 1:6 for 950 sq m?",
  "response": "To calculate the quantity of cement and sand required for plastering, we need to follow several steps:\n\n### Step 1: Calculate the Volume of Plaster\nFirst, determine the total volume of plaster needed for 950 sq.m area with 12mm thickness.\n- Area = 950 sq.m\n- Thickness = 12 mm = 0.012 m\n\n\\[ \\text{Volume} = \\text{Area} \\times \\text{Thickness} \\]\n\\[ \\text{Volume} = 950 \\, \\text{sq.m} \\times 0.012 \\, \\text{m} \\]\n\\[ \\text{Volume} = 11.4 \\, \\text{cubic meters} \\]\n\n### Step 2: Calculate the Dry Volume\nSince the wet volume is usually increased by 33% to account for dry volume:\n\\[ \\text{Dry Volume} = \\text{Wet Volume} \\times 1.33 \\]\n\\[ \\text{Dry Volume} = 11.4 \\times 1.33 = 15.162 \\, \\text{cubic meters} \\]\n\n### Step 3: Determine the Cement and Sand Quantities\nUsing the mix ratio 1:6 (cement:sand), the total parts are 1+6=7.\n\n#### Cement Quantity:\n\\[ \\text{Cement Volume} = \\frac{\\text{Dry Volume}}{\\text{Total Parts}} \\times \\text{Cement Part} \\]\n\\[ \\text{Cement Volume} = \\frac{15.162}{7} \\times 1 \\]\n\\[ \\text{Cement Volume} \\approx 2.166 \\, \\text{cubic meters} \\]\n\n#### Sand Quantity:\n\\[ \\text{Sand Volume} = \\frac{\\text{Dry Volume}}{\\text{Total Parts}} \\times \\text{Sand Part} \\]\n\\[ \\text{Sand Volume} = \\frac{15.162}{7} \\times 6 \\]\n\\[ \\text{Sand Volume} \\approx 13 \\, \\text{cubic meters} \\]\n\n### Step 4: Convert Cement Volume to Bags\nFor practical purposes, cement is measured in bags. One cubic meter of cement is approximately equivalent to 28.8 bags (assuming 1 bag = 50 kg and the density of cement is around 1440 kg per cubic meter).\n\n\\[ \\text{Number of Cement Bags} = 2.166 \\times 28.8 \\approx 62.38 \\]\n\n### Summary\nFor 950 sq.m of area with 12mm thickness plastering using 1:6 mix ratio:\n- **Cement:** Approximately 2.166 cubic meters or around 62 bags.\n- **Sand:** Approximately 13 cubic meters.\n\nEnsure to account for wastage and variations in mix application.",
